The gender of the day is chaos in the form of confusing kindness.  I will not be elaborating.
Either way, no matter what kind of character you bring to the table, be respectful and choose kindness.  Love you all!

Have conversations with people who identify in the same way as your character, so that when you slip into that role you can be more authentic.  And at the end of your session, you decide that this character is just that- a character- then at least you know for sure.

If you are (for example) a cishet male, and you are playing a character who doesn't fit that description?  PLEASE be aware of the caricatures and stereotypes that can present themselves, and try to avoid them.

TTRPGs offer a unique lens through which we can view ourselves, and allow a level of self-discovery that no other media can match.  If you want to play a character who is a different gender/orientation, go for it.

In the case of Joe Rogan?  I legitimately do not give a fuck if he has a podcast or not.  Dude's got enough money to live comfortably for the rest of a couple lifetimes, he's going to be fine.

How many people have to die before we start holding the anti-science influencers responsible in some capacity?  Demonitize the anti-science episodes, levvy fines, make these influencers interview *actual* scientists- there are so many ways that we can hold someone accountable.

Those statements convince people to not do everything they can to protect others, and that directly leads to more deaths.  Should Joe Rogan be held accountable as if he had killed people personally?  Absolutely not.  But we are in a pandemic that has lasted two years.

But we have a body count in this country of over 900,000 covid-related deaths, and when influential people tell 11 million listeners that the vaccine is pointless, or that testing is pointless, or that masks don't work, or that ivermectin and hydroxychloriquine work?

Now, if this lie was just more right-wing nonsense about how 45 was awesome or something stupid like that, I wouldn't care.  I would continue to live my life with him in the same category as Alex Jones, and his podcast would just be one more podcast that I didn't listen to.

So, here's my $0.02.  Could we go this route?  Absolutely.  And we should.  However, think of the precident that this sets.  Joe Rogan reaches roughly 11 million people every week, and has told lie after lie after lie that he has tried to pass off as fact. https://t.co/EWTtTTq02g

So...  yeah.  I like Star Wars.  ALL of Star Wars.  Because it's a beautiful story about space wizards.

But the prequel movies are still an amazing addition to the Star Wars lore by themselves, and without them we wouldn't have gotten the groundwork for the Clone Wars series, Rebels, Jedi: Fallen Order, The Force: Unleashed, or countless other incredible storylines.

The prequels get a lot of hate, and yes there are parts that suck SO HARD.  But the OT had cringe-worthy parts, too, and just as many.
- Leia kissing her brother
- Boba Fett getting killed because Han literally just turned around
- Luke's general whiny-ness
- The Death Star

The cinematography in the prequels, as well as the art of the backdrops of Coruscaunt, Naboo, and Geonosis, were FANTASTIC, and as much as I hate the "one planet one biome" trope, the worlds themselves were wonderfully constructed.

Zam Wesell got ROBBED of her story.  A changeling bounty hunter, whose species had never been seen before?  And she only managed to get, what, 4 lines before she was killed by Jango Fett?  We deserved more Zam Wesell storyline.
Obi-wan's sass in AotC is UNMATCHED.  Ewan McGregor breathed a life into this character that Sir Alec Guinness never did, and it turned Obi-wan into a character that was actually interesting.

His battle with Yoda was.... odd, sure, but it showed just how powerful Yoda was, as well- which was something that until AotC had only been hinted at.  He trained Luke, and talked to Obi-wan's force ghost, but we never got to see how this dyslexic frog became YODA until now.

Count Dooku was a compelling and complicated villain that really showed that it wasn't just the Emperor that was able to spread evil from behind a public face, and his force abilities were on par with Sidious himself (from what we'd seen so far).

The clones were an amazing expansion that took a single throwaway line (Luke: "You fought in the Clone Wars?") and made an entire plot that made you care about the people involved. Yoda's struggle to see through the fog of the Dark Side added tension and flaws to the jedi.

Hot take (apparently):

The prequels as a whole didn't suck.
